   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28601_1824_03_02_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1824-03-02">March 2 1824</date>
                  <lb/>
               </dateline>
               <salute>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName>
                  <lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> having answered<lb/>
               you about the Atlas I<lb/>
               need not say or do any<lb/>
               more on that subject-.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               For <title ref="./Workography.xml#Works1">
                  <hi rend="underline">Parks</hi> Edition of<lb/>
               the poets</title> - read<lb/>
               Sharpes Ed<hi rend="superscript">n</hi> of the poets<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriet</persName> had by mistake<lb/>
               written <hi rend="underline">Parks</hi> on your list<lb/>
                  - I think <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeS1">Sophy</persName> would<lb/>
               prefer <title ref="./Workography.xml#Works1">Sharpe's Ed<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>
               </title> to any<lb/>
               other because that is the<lb/>
               Ed<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">her father</persName> gave <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriet</persName>
               <lb/>
               and they have read the<lb/>
               books together &amp; learned<lb/>
               passages in them together<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28601_1824_03_02_page02.jpg"/>
               
               &amp; might like to refer to<lb/>
               the old marked passages<lb/>
               &amp;c - But if it should<lb/>
               not be easily to be procured<lb/>
               or if you see cause to<lb/>
               buy any other you are<lb/>
               requested to use your<lb/>
               own discretion -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Add to periodical<lb/>
               works in your list<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Mirro1">The Mirror</title> &amp; <title ref="./Workography.xml#Loung1">the Lounger</title>
               <lb/>
               which I think will be<lb/>
               particularly<lb/>
                  acceptable to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeS1">Sophy</persName> &amp; since<lb/>
               her acquaintance with<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#Janus1">Edinburgh</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Can you think of any<lb/>
               works within our compass<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28601_1824_03_02_page03.jpg"/>
               
               as to price which would<lb/>
                  serve instead of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Cyclo1">Rees</title> or<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Edinb1">Brewsters Encyclopedia</title>
               <lb/>
               for a book of reference<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <orig>Q<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg>Question</reg>
               </choice> Old <title ref="./Workography.xml#Chamb1">Chambers</title>? -<lb/>
               I suppose a few plays<lb/>
               might be agreeable - but<lb/>
               it is very difficult to get<lb/>
               a good selection.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Now I am going to<lb/>
               plague you upon quite<lb/>
               another subject - and<lb/>
               you may take your own<lb/>
               time for what follows<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The last travelling<lb/>
               carriage which I hired from<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Halton_ENK">Halton</placeName> had two seats - one<lb/>
               before for my sisters - the<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28601_1824_03_02_page04.jpg"/>
               
               other behind for a servant<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>We found this very conve<lb/>
               nient especially when we<lb/>
               were staying at houses where<lb/>
               the young people liked to<lb/>
               drive out with us - . But<lb/>
               there is one objection to the<lb/>
               baruche seat in front, that<lb/>
               those within the carriage<lb/>
               have their view obstructed<lb/>
               even when the baruche seat<lb/>
               is <hi rend="underline">empty</hi> - When it is filled<lb/>
               they must submit - But<lb/>
               when empty why should<lb/>
               not the baruche seat be<lb/>
               made so as to be easily<lb/>
               removed?<lb/>
                  1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi>.. <choice>
                  <orig>Q<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>Question</reg>
               </choice>- Is any baruche seat<lb/>
               now made for this purpose<lb/>
                  2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. <choice>
                  <orig>Q<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>Question</reg>
               </choice> - Could a <add>light</add> seat be made<lb/>
                  of cane like what <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">my<lb/>
               Father</persName> formerly had<lb/>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28601_1824_03_02_page05.jpg"/>
               
               had) which was fastened<lb/>
               to the <hi rend="underline">body</hi> of the carriage<lb/>
               - Could this light seat<lb/>
               instead of being <choice>
                  <orig>perma-<lb/>
                  nently</orig>
                  <reg>permanently</reg>
               </choice> fastened to the<lb/>
               body be hooked on staples<lb/>
               - and when not used as<lb/>
               a seat be unhooked &amp;<lb/>
               lowered till <del>the</del> it no longer<lb/>
               interferes with the view<lb/>
               from the chaise windows<lb/>
               &amp; then hook it on other<lb/>
               staples &amp; strap it below<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <orig>Q<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>Question</reg>
               </choice> 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. If staples &amp; hooks<lb/>
               are objectionable - could<lb/>
               the seat be hinged at<lb/>
               back<lb/>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28601_1824_03_02_page06.jpg"/>
               
               with stout hinges to<lb/>
               the body of the carriage<lb/>
               &amp; be supported when<lb/>
               up by irons such as -<lb/>
               support disks fastened<lb/>
               to a wall; which irons<lb/>
               turn on a ring at one end<lb/>
               &amp; hook into a staple in<lb/>
               the under part of the board<lb/>
               - the irons fall down out<lb/>
               of the way when not used<lb/>
               &amp; in this case behind<lb/>
               hidden by the seat letting<lb/>
               down like a leaf before<lb/>
               them would be no <choice>
                  <orig>dis-<lb/>
                  sight</orig>
                  <reg>dissight</reg>
               </choice>-<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Could the seat be<lb/>
               pushed up by spiral<lb/>
               iron springs like those used<lb/>
               <pb n="7" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28601_1824_03_02_page07.jpg"/>
               
               in carriage lamps to push<lb/>
               up the candles?<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I am aware that the<lb/>
               expense of executing<lb/>
               any thing new in<lb/>
               a carriage is consider<lb/>
               able - and am not<lb/>
               going my dear friend<lb/>
               to plunge into any<lb/>
               folly of this sort - But<lb/>
               I should like to know<lb/>
               from you &amp; any coach-<lb/>
               maker you depend upon<lb/>
               whether such a plan<lb/>
               <orig>
                  <orig>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg>would</reg>
               </orig> be feasible.
              </p>
            <lb/>
            <closer>
               <choice>
                  <orig>yr</orig>
                  <reg>your</reg>
               </choice>
               <choice>
                  <orig>affec<hi rend="superscript">ly</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>affectionately</reg>
               </choice>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">M E</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <pb n="8" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28601_1824_03_02_page08.jpg"/>
            <closer>
               <note>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edg.</persName>
                  <lb/>
               2 Mr. -/24<lb/>
               Partic. of her Carriage</note>
               <lb/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. Beaufort Ret.</persName>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
      </body>
